Unbeaten Italy Wins Again 
World champions Italy remained unbeaten in the World Cup men's
volleyball tournament, downing Cuba on Tuesday to extend their records
8-0 in Japan's Sendai.
The Italians, who only lost two sets in the previous seven matches,
lost their third set in the 12-team event before outplaying Cuba 15-12,
7-15, 15-8, 15-3.
In other matches in Sendai on Tuesday, Brazil ousted Canada 15-5, 15-4,
15-6, and the United States defeated hosts Japan 15-7, 15-12, 15-9.
In Fukushima, the Netherlands downed Argentina 15-7, 15-2, 15-6. South
Korea fought off Egypt 15-10, 15-7, 15-1 while China surged back with
one set down to overcome African champions Tunisia 11-15, 15-7, 15-7,
15-7.
So far, the Netherlands, the United States and Japan all have 6-2
records, followed by Cuba, which has five wins against three losses.
Argentina, South Korea and China stood with a 3-5 record, Canada and
Egypt 1-7 and Tunisia 0-7.
There are only three matches left for each of the 12 teams. The top
three will win Atlanta Olympic berths while the United States has got a
ticket as the host.
